{"title_page": "2020 United States presidential election in Florida", "text_new": "{{main|2020 United States presidential election}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2020 [[United States presidential election]] in Florida\n| country = Florida\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 2016 United States presidential election in Florida\n| previous_year     = 2016\n| election_date = November 3, 2020\n| next_election     = 2024 United States presidential election in Florida\n| next_year         = 2024\n| turnout = %\n| image_size = \n\n| image1 = Donald Trump official portrait (cropped).jpg\n| nominee1 = [[Donald Trump]]\n| party1 = Republican Party (United States)\n| home_state1 = [[Florida]]\n| running_mate1 = [[Mike Pence]]\n| electoral_vote1 =\n| popular_vote1 = \n| percentage1 = \n\n| image2 = Joe Biden 2013.jpg\n| nominee2 = [[Joe Biden]]\n| party2 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| home_state2 = [[Delaware]]\n| running_mate2 = TBA\n| electoral_vote2 =\n| popular_vote2 = \n| percentage2 = \n\n| title = President\n| before_election = [[Donald Trump]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = TBA\n| after_party = \n}}\n{{ElectionsFL}}\n\nThe '''2020 United States presidential election in Florida''' is scheduled to take place on Tuesday, November 3, 2020, as part of the [[2020 United States elections]] in which all 50 states plus the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]] will participate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-elections-key-dates-midterms-2020-presidential-house-congress-senate-a8472821.html|title=US elections key dates: When are the 2018 midterms and the 2020 presidential campaign?|last=Kelly|first=Ben|date=August 13, 2018|work=[[The Independent]]|access-date=January 3, 2019}}</ref> [[Florida]] voters will choose electors to represent them in the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]] via a popular vote. The state of Florida has 29 electoral votes in the Electoral College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.archives.gov/federal-register/electoral-college/allocation.html|title=Distribution of Electoral Votes|last=|first=|date=|website=[[National Archives and Records Administration]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=January 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Miami Beach, Florida]], which hosted the [[1972 Democratic National Convention]], was a finalist to host the [[2020 Democratic National Convention]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/miami-beach/article213670709.html|title=Cruise ship hotels, zoo parties and an NBA arena: Miami's Democratic convention pitch|work=miamiherald|access-date=July 1, 2018}}</ref> The other finalists were Milwaukee and Houston. Milwaukee was ultimately decided as the host.<ref name=\":0FL\">{{Cite news|url=https://fox6now.com/2018/06/20/city-of-milwaukee-named-as-1-of-3-finalists-to-host-2020-dnc-convention/|title=City of Milwaukee 1 of 3 finalists to host 2020 Democratic National Convention|date=2018-06-20|work=FOX6Now.com|access-date=2018-07-01|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/08/22/dnc-team-visiting-milwaukee-2020-democratic-convention-site/1065267002/|title=Selection committee for 2020 Democratic Convention will visit Milwaukee next week|last=Glauber|first=Bill|date=August 22, 2018|work=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|accessdate=August 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFlorida will also be incumbent president Donald Trump's home state for this election, after having identified New York as his home in 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/31/us/politics/trump-new-york-florida-primary-residence.html|title=Trump, Lifelong New Yorker, Declares Himself a Resident of Florida|last=Haberman|first=Maggie|date=November 4, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref> As a result, Trump became the first nominee of either major party to be from Florida.\n\n==Primary elections==\nThe primary elections were held on March 17, 2020.\n\n===Republican primary===\nThe Florida secretary of state declared [[Rocky de la Fuente]] to be a major candidate and thus worthy of automatic inclusion on the ballot.\n \n{{excerpt|2020 Florida Republican primary|fragment=FLresults}}\n\n===Democratic primary===\nThree Democrats were still in race by the time Florida held its primaries: [[Vermont]] [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Bernie Sanders]], former [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]] [[Joe Biden]], and [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] from [[Hawaii]] [[Tulsi Gabbard]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Kate |title=Elizabeth Warren Formally Announces 2020 Presidential Bid in Lawrence, Mass. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/09/us/politics/elizabeth-warren-2020.html |accessdate=10 February 2019 |publisher=The New York Times |date=9 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Zhou |first1=Li |title=Kamala Harris announces her historic 2020 presidential campaign |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/1/21/18175628/kamala-harris-2020-campaign-president |accessdate=10 February 2019 |publisher=Vox |date=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Detrow |first1=Scott |title=Cory Booker Makes It Official: He's Running For President In 2020 |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/02/01/676578945/cory-booker-makes-it-official-hes-running-for-president-in-2020 |accessdate=10 February 2019 |publisher=NPR |date=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first Democratic debate took place in [[Miami]] over two nights at the end of June 2019. It was broadcast on several of the [[NBC]] networks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/first-democratic-debate-2020-election|title=First Democratic Debate 2019: Highlights, candidates and more|website=NBC News}}</ref>\n\n{{excerpt|2020 Florida Democratic primary|fragment=FLresults}}\n\n==General election==\n===Predictions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Source\n!Ranking\n!As of\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[The Cook Political Report]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cookpolitical.com/sites/default/files/2020-03/EC%20030920.4.pdf|title=2020 POTUS Race ratings|website=The Cook Political Report|language=en|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Tossup}}\n|March 9, 2020\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Stuart Rothenberg|Inside Elections]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insideelections.com/ratings/president|title=POTUS Ratings {{!}} Inside Elections|website=insideelections.com|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Tossup}}\n|April 3, 2020\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Sabato's Crystal Ball]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://centerforpolitics.org/crystalball/2020-president/|title=Larry J. Sabato's Crystal Ball \u00bb 2020 President|website=crystalball.centerforpolitics.org|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Lean|R}}\n|April 2, 2020\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Politico]]<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.politico.com/2020-election/race-forecasts-and-predictions/president/ |title=2020 Election Forecast|date=November 19, 2019 |publisher=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Tossup}}\n|November 19, 2019\n|}\n\n===Polling===\n====Aggregate polls====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n!colspan=\"7\"|Donald Trump vs. Joe Biden\n|-\n!Source of poll aggregation\n!Dates administered\n!Dates updated\n![[Joe Biden]]\n![[Donald Trump]]\n!Other/Undecided{{Efn|Calculated by taking the difference of 100% and all other candidates combined.|name=|group=}}\n!Margin\n|-\n|[https://www.270towin.com/2020-polls-biden-trump/florida/ 270 to Win]\n|March 16,2020 - April 6,2020\n|April 6,2020\n|{{party shading/Democratic}}|'''45.5%'''\n|44.0%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}}|{{hs|1.5}}'''Biden + 1.5'''\n|-\n|[https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2020/president/fl/florida_trump_vs_biden-6841.html Real Clear Politics]\n|March 5,2020 \u2013 April 4, 2020\n|April 4, 2020\n|{{party shading/Democratic}}|'''46.7%'''\n|46.3%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic